You can use [String#contentEquals][1] if one the operands is a `String`. If not, you can first call `toString()` on one of them.

In the past, I have lost hours while debugging string equality problems and I am not satisfied by the justification in the [API reference][2]. As of Java 8, [CharSequence][2] could be defined as follows to allow arbitrary `CharSequence`&#39;s to be compared. Classes could then override the default implementation of `equals(CharSequence)` to increase performance, just like what `String` does in `contentEquals()`.

```
public interface CharSequence {
	int length();
	char charAt(int index);
	CharSequence subSequence(int start, int end);
	
	default boolean equals(CharSequence s) {
		if (s == null || length() != s.length())
			return false;
		for (int i = 0; i &lt; length(); i++)
			if (charAt(i) != s.charAt(i))
				return false;
		return true;
	}
}
```

[1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/String.html#contentEquals-java.lang.CharSequence-
[2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/lang/CharSequence.html

